            content: "<p>Prime Minister Keir Starmer and Conservative (Tory) Party leader Kemi Badenoch engaged in a heated clash over the government's defence investment plan during Prime Minister's Questions (PMQs) in the House of Commons. This debate reflects rising political tension surrounding UK defence budget policy amid ongoing global geopolitical pressure.</p><p>Badenoch strongly criticized Starmer's government defence investment plan, arguing the move was inadequate to maintain UK national security amid rising global geopolitical threats. Meanwhile, Starmer defended his policy, asserting his government had allocated a responsible defence budget while maintaining the nation's fiscal discipline.</p><p>This debate occurred amid pressure from NATO allies for member states to increase their defence spending, in line with rising security concerns across Europe. The defence issue has become one of the main friction points between the government and opposition ahead of the imminent leadership transition period following Starmer's resignation.</p><p>This tension surrounding defence policy also highlights the challenges any future UK government will face in balancing national security investment needs against still-limited domestic fiscal conditions, given other spending priorities such as healthcare and cost of living also demand serious attention from the state budget.</p>",
